<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic rule in the US is that, if you opera=
te a stock exchange, you need to register with the US Securities and Exchan=
ge Commission as a national stock exchange. This comes with a lot of oversi=
ght; in particular, the rules of your exchange have to be published and tra=
nsparent and approved by the SEC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose you could debate what qualifies as a=
 stock exchange. Roughly, an exchange is a venue for bringing together buye=
rs and sellers of stock so they can trade with each other, but in modern fi=
nance there are gray areas. There are some things that look sort of like st=
ock exchanges =E2=80=94 dark pools,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1=
L2RlZmluaXRpb25zL2luZGV4LnBocD93aWR0aD04NDAmaGVpZ2h0PTgwMCZpZnJhbWU9dHJ1ZSZ=
kZWZfaWQ9NGY0ZTNhZTI2NTI3MGNhYTdjZWViZTg5ZDE2N2QwMGImdGVybV9vY2N1cj05OTkmdG=
VybV9zcmM9VGl0bGU6MTc6Q2hhcHRlcjpJSTpQYXJ0OjI0MjoyNDIuMzAx/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB39c791e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">alternative trading systems</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94 t=
hat are not actually registered as stock exchanges. But they are=C2=A0<a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9kaXZpc2lvbnMvbWFya2V0cmVnL2Zvcm0tYXRzLW4tZmlsaW5ncy5odG=
0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaa86749c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">registered with the SEC</a>=C2=
=A0too, and the SEC also supervises their operations. For that matter there=
 are stockbrokers: A broker=E2=80=99s website and mobile app can look and f=
eel a bit like a stock exchange, to a retail customer; you can log onto Rob=
inhood and see prices and buy and sell stock. But <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZWNmci5nb3Y=
vY3VycmVudC90aXRsZS0xNy9jaGFwdGVyLUlJL3BhcnQtMjQwL3N1YnBhcnQtQS9zdWJqZWN0LW=
dyb3VwLUVDRlI3OTI4NzY2NGMzMjczNDEvc2VjdGlvbi0yNDAuM2ItMTY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB7ba41b0d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> there are rules</a> distinguishing brokers from =
exchanges (a broker mostly does not provide a platform for people to trade =
with each other, but routes orders to other market venues), and anyway brok=
er-dealers are=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>registered with the SEC. Also stock=
=C2=A0<em>clearinghouses=C2=A0</em>(which settle trades, moving stock from =
the seller to the buyer) have to register.=C2=A0Basically any stock-exchang=
e-like thing has to register with the SEC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, these are not really rules about=C2=A0<em=
>stock=C2=A0</em>exchanges; technically the rules are about=C2=A0<em>securi=
ties</em>, not stocks. If you run an exchange-like thing for trading securi=
ties =E2=80=94=C2=A0stocks, bonds, options, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0you have to=
 register with the SEC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are crypto exchanges in the US. They ope=
rate as exchanges (venues for bringing together buyers and sellers), and al=
so often as clearinghouses (they move tokens from sellers to buyers<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>). They are not generally registered with the SEC as securities exchang=
es (or ATSs, or clearinghouses).=C2=A0They offer trading in crypto tokens. =
Some of those tokens =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bitcoin, Ether =E2=80=94=C2=A0are not s=
ecurities.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But the SEC takes the view =E2=80=94=C2=A0in speeches, in various=
 enforcement actions =E2=80=94=C2=A0that almost all of them are securities.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This means that most crypto exchanges that ope=
rate in the US are probably, in the SEC=E2=80=99s view, breaking the law. I=
 assert this pretty confidently based on my reading of the SEC=E2=80=99s wh=
ole vibe, but the SEC has not really come out and said it directly, by, you=
 know, bringing enforcement cases against crypto exchanges. It has come clo=
se. Last year it brought an insider trading case against a former Coinbase =
Global Inc. employee, accusing him of insider trading some tokens that Coin=
base listed; the SEC claimed that these tokens were securities, and <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6L=
y90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9tYXR0X2xldmluZS9zdGF0dXMvMTU1MDIwMjAzNjU3MDAxNzc5Mg/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB0de8bc42" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I tweeted</a> =E2=80=9CThis is a wei=
rd way for the SEC to say that Coinbase is running an illegal securities ex=
change?=E2=80=9D Last month the SEC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjMvdGhlLXNlYy1pcy1jb21pbmctZm9yLWNvaW5iYXNlP2Nt=
cGlkPUJCRDA0MTcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXd=
zbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDQxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB54c11be9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">  sent a Wells notice to Coinbase</a>, basi=
cally telling Coinbase that it is=C2=A0<em>going=C2=A0</em>to bring charges=
 against it for operating an illegal securities exchange. But not yet.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLX=
JlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy03OA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5b3c471c" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the SEC br=
ought charges against Bittrex Inc.</a> for allegedly operating an illegal s=
ecurities exchange:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today c=
harged crypto asset trading platform Bittrex, Inc. and its co-founder and f=
ormer CEO William Shihara for operating an unregistered national securities=
 exchange, broker, and clearing agency. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since at least 2014, Bittrex has held itself o=
ut as a platform that facilitated buying and selling of crypto assets that =
the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint alleges were offered and sold as securities. Fr=
om 2017 through 2022, Bittrex earned at least $1.3 billion in revenues from=
, among other things, transaction fees from investors, including U.S. inves=
tors, while servicing them as a broker, exchange, and clearing agency witho=
ut registering any of these activities with the Commission.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9u=
L2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMy9jb21wLXByMjAyMy03OC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB05=
527160" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint</a>, which is=C2=A0straightfor=
ward. Bittrex is an exchange (and a broker, and a clearinghouse). It lists =
a bunch of tokens. Some of them, in the SEC=E2=80=99s view, are securities.=
 =E2=80=9CFor purposes of prevailing on the Exchange Act claims set forth h=
erein, the SEC need<br />only establish that Bittrex transacted in a single=
 crypto asset security,=E2=80=9D says the complaint, but then it goes on to=
 list six crypto tokens that the SEC is pretty sure are securities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here again the argument is straightforward and=
 familiar. The US Supreme Court <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jb3JwZmluL2ZyYW1ld=
29yay1pbnZlc3RtZW50LWNvbnRyYWN0LWFuYWx5c2lzLWRpZ2l0YWwtYXNzZXRz/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBabed6677" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> has said</a> that a =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=
=80=9D includes =E2=80=9Cthe investment of money in a common enterprise wit=
h a reasonable expectation of profits to be derived from the efforts of oth=
ers.=E2=80=9D Lots and lots of crypto projects raised money from investors =
by promising to build some sort of profitable product or ecosystem on the b=
lockchain. The SEC cites some of them.</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Algorand is a blockchain protocol founded by S=
ilvio Micali. The Algorand blockchain uses a consensus algorithm it calls =
=E2=80=9Cpure proof-of-stake,=E2=80=9D in which each user=E2=80=99s ability=
 to influence the choice of a new block is proportional to its stake (numbe=
r of tokens) in the system.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CALGO=E2=80=9D is the native token of =
the Algorand blockchain, and has a maximum supply of 10 billion ALGO minted=
 at the launch of the Algorand network. Because ALGO is the native token of=
 the Algorand blockchain, those utilizing the Algorand blockchain need to h=
old (and potentially stake) certain amounts of ALGO.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Algorand Foundation Ltd. (the =E2=80=9CAlg=
orand Foundation=E2=80=9D) conducted an initial ALGO token sale on or about=
 June 19, 2019, selling 25 million tokens at $2.40 per ALGO, raising approx=
imately $60 million. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The publicly available information disseminate=
d by Algorand, Inc. and the Algorand Foundation led ALGO investors to reaso=
nably expect to profit from Algorand, Inc.=E2=80=99s and the Algorand Found=
ation=E2=80=99s efforts to grow the Algorand protocol, which would in turn =
potentially increase demand for, and therefore the value of, the ALGO token=
 itself. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Algorand Foundation described =E2=80=9CGov=
ernance=E2=80=9D as a way for investors to make investment returns on their=
 ALGO purchases=E2=80=94stating it is =E2=80=9Ca decentralized program whic=
h allows Algo holders to vote on the future of Algorand=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9Cthe best way to earn rewards for holding Algo, with APY% of 10.02% - 14.=
05% seen in previous periods.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Algorand, Inc. and Algorand Foundation web=
sites tout their teams=E2=80=99 technical experience and expertise in the a=
reas of cryptography and business development. For example, Algorand, Inc.=
=E2=80=99s website states: =E2=80=9CBlending technical mastery and professi=
onal stability, the Algorand team consists of internationally recognized re=
searchers, mathematicians, cryptographers, and economists along with proven=
 business leaders from global technology companies.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of this stuff even sounds particularly ba=
d. But the bones of it are:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Algorand (and lots of other crypto pro=
jects) raised money from investors to build its project.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The investors expected to make money from their in=
vestment in this enterprise.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They =
expected to make this money because of =E2=80=9Cthe efforts of others=E2=80=
=9D: The team promoting the project (and raising the money) was also going =
to build it, and the investors were hoping for a return because they though=
t the team would do a good job.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s just stock. There=E2=80=99s a b=
lockchain, sure, and the mechanics of how ALGO tokens participate in the up=
side of the Algorand blockchain are somewhat different from the mechanics o=
f how META shares participate in the upside of Meta Platforms Inc. But basi=
cally, the SEC says,=C2=A0this is stock: You invest money in a team that is=
 building a tech project, and if the project works out you get rich. Bittre=
x was offering this stock on its exchange. So it should have registered as =
a stock exchange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The complaint also details that Bittrex kind o=
f knew this:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When deciding whether to include a=
n asset on the Bittrex Platform, Bittrex assessed whether the financial ben=
efits of doing so outweighed the risk that the asset in question would be s=
ubject to scrutiny by regulators, including specifically the SEC. For examp=
le, in or around March 2017, Shihara told the other Bittrex co-founders wit=
h regards to a particular crypto asset: =E2=80=9Cthe problem is that its go=
ing to be seen by the SEC as a security. im meeting with these guys face to=
 face to get specifics on how much they want to raise, who they are raising=
 it from, and what they expect the after market to be. its a big enough opp=
ortunity that we might want to roll the dice on the sec investigation. we h=
ave a couple of paths forward but one idea was to have them take a position=
 in bittrex and own the risk of an SEC investigation with us.=E2=80=9D</p><=
/blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To further its dual goals of making more crypt=
o assets available on the Bittrex Platform and avoiding regulatory scrutiny=
, starting in at least May 2017, Bittrex routinely directed that crypto ass=
et issuers =E2=80=9Cscrub=E2=80=9D their offering and marketing materials o=
f =E2=80=9Cinvestment-related terms,=E2=80=9D including language that would=
 =E2=80=9Cget unwanted attention from the SEC.=E2=80=9D Bittrex regularly a=
sked issuers to remove =E2=80=9Cproblematic statements=E2=80=9D from their =
marketing materials=E2=80=94statements indicating that the asset was market=
ed as a security=E2=80=94as a prerequisite for making the issuers=E2=80=99 =
crypto assets available for trading on the Bittrex Platform. Bittrex unoffi=
cially dubbed this practice the =E2=80=9Cproblematic statement cleanup.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The =E2=80=9Cproblematic statement cleanup=E2=
=80=9D was nearly always done after the initial offering of the crypto asse=
t=E2=80=94i.e., after the crypto asset had already been offered and sold to=
 investors. In other=C2=A0words, the issuers of the crypto assets had alrea=
dy marketed, offered, and sold the crypto assets to the investing public by=
 using the very =E2=80=9Cproblematic statements=E2=80=9D that Bittrex recog=
nized were =E2=80=9Cinvestment-related terms=E2=80=9D that indicated the as=
sets could be securities. In requiring issuers to =E2=80=9Cscrub=E2=80=9D t=
heir documents, Bittrex did not actually change the economic reality of tho=
se offers and sales, but rather simply attempted to remove or =E2=80=9Cscru=
b=E2=80=9D any evidence of these public statements without changing the act=
ual characteristics of the offering or asset even assuming the deletions we=
re successful.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC quotes a =E2=80=9Ccheat sheet=E2=80=9D=
 that Bittrex gave its employees to flag bad features of crypto tokens. One=
 =E2=80=9Ccommon problematic feature=E2=80=9D is =E2=80=9CTokens providing=
=C2=A0passive income (e.g. dividends, buy back and burning of tokens),=E2=
=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and one =E2=80=9Ccommon problematic statement=E2=80=9D is =E2=80=
=9C[proof of work] and [proof of stake] rewards described as token holders =
receiving =E2=80=98interest.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D That is, the common=C2=A0<em=
>economic=C2=A0</em>features of crypto tokens =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ways that =
a token participates in the upside of its project, either through token buy=
backs or through issuance of new tokens to holders =E2=80=94=C2=A0run the r=
isk of turning them into securities, <em>according to Bittrex</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The complaint also explains=C2=A0<em>why=C2=A0=
</em>the SEC cares about this, why it thinks that the system of securities =
exchange registration matters. One aspect of it is that, in traditional fin=
ance, brokers and exchanges and clearinghouses tend to be=C2=A0<em>differen=
t entities</em>; there is a lot of intermediation in traditional finance, w=
here regular customers access the market through their broker=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0website, brokers trade on a separate stock exchange, and settlement happ=
ens through a separate clearinghouse.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto has enthusiastically disintermediated t=
his: Retail traders open accounts directly on the crypto exchange, and the =
exchange matches trades, holds everyone=E2=80=99s crypto for them and settl=
es trades. A year ago a lot of people in crypto would have told you that th=
is was good and efficient, that they had cut out the layers of wasteful mid=
dlemen in traditional finance. Then FTX failed and took billions of dollars=
 of customer money with it and, you know, that position is more controversi=
al.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC endorses the traditional system:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Separation of these core functions aims to min=
imize conflicts between the interests of securities intermediaries and inve=
stors. Registration provides the means for the SEC to understand the busine=
ss of the securities intermediaries and their relationship with investors i=
n order to protect those investors and the securities markets, and to preve=
nt fraud or other abuses.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors in traditional national securities m=
arkets do not generally trade directly with national securities exchanges o=
r clearing agencies but instead are customers of broker-dealers.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC also makes the point that traditional =
stock exchanges have to have published transparent rules, including about h=
ow they list and delist stocks. Crypto exchanges don=E2=80=99t:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By contrast, a crypto asset platform that fail=
s to register in any capacity declares itself free from any obligation to f=
ollow those provisions in the Exchange Act, including the types of rules de=
scribed above, that are designed to protect investors, promote the public i=
nterest, and provide truthful and material information to investors. As a r=
esult, investors are at the whim of the crypto asset platform to give them =
information about their standards and procedures for listing (and de-listin=
g) investments, about the investments themselves, including whether any par=
ticular listed crypto asset may potentially be delisted, and the platform=
=E2=80=99s operations.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A private conversation in or around June 2017 =
between a Bittrex employee and one of Bittrex=E2=80=99s three founders illu=
strates the type of investor harm that can result from a crypto asset platf=
orm failing to follow or even recognize these obligations. The employee com=
plained to the founder: =E2=80=9CI hate people bitching that we don=E2=80=
=99t email them about market removals=E2=80=A6I LOST SO MUCH CAUSE I DIDn=
=E2=80=99T KNOW.=E2=80=9D The founder responded that his preferred response=
 to those investors was =E2=80=9Cgo f*** yourself=E2=80=9D or at a minimum =
to tell them to =E2=80=9Ctrack your own damn investment or get a broker to =
do it for you.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSeattle-based Bittrex was already pre=
pared to wind down its U.S. operations,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9h=
cnRpY2xlcy9zZWMtdGFyZ2V0cy1iaXR0cmV4LWZhbGxlbi1naWFudC1vZi11LXMtY3J5cHRvLWV=
4Y2hhbmdlcy00YmQ2MTViNj9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB667196c1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> reports the Wall Street Journal</a>, =E2=80=9Cciting t=
he difficulty of working with U.S. regulators that have taken enforcement a=
ction against over 100 crypto defendants in six years.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which: yes.=C2=A0If you run a crypto exchange =
and you come into the SEC and say =E2=80=9Cwe want to register as a securit=
ies=C2=A0exchange so we can let our customers trade securities tokens on ou=
r website,=E2=80=9D the SEC will stop you right there and say =E2=80=9CWait=
: customers? Website? No no no no no, if you are an=C2=A0<em>exchange</em>,=
 you can=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0<em>customers</em>, or a=C2=A0<em>website</em>=
; that=E2=80=99s for=C2=A0<em>brokers</em>. You can=E2=80=99t come in here =
and register a securities exchange with <em>customers</em>.=E2=80=9D And th=
en you go away, confused and sad and probably sued. There is a traditional =
financial system, and crypto has built a different system, and the SEC has =
pretty much everywhere said =E2=80=9Cnah, you gotta follow the traditional =
system.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And crypto people have said =E2=80=9Cwell we can=E2=
=80=99t really do that because ...=E2=80=9D and the SEC has said =E2=80=9Cs=
hh, shh, we don=E2=80=99t care.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so last week the SEC <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmd=
vdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy03Nw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa5642b91" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> issued an update on a proposed rule</a>=C2=A0updating the definiti=
on of =E2=80=9Cexchange=E2=80=9D to, among other things, cover decentralize=
d-finance crypto exchanges. Republican SEC Commissioner Hester Peirce <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3N0YXRlbWVudC9wZWlyY2UtcmVuZGVyaW5nLWlub3ZhdGlvbi=
0yMDIzLTA0LTEy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB018cdaa1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> dissented</a>, c=
omplaining that =E2=80=9Crather than embracing the promise of new technolog=
y as we have done in the past, here we propose to embrace stagnation, force=
 centralization, urge expatriation, and welcome extinction of new technolog=
y.=E2=80=9D Her point is that crypto exchanges have built innovative new wa=
ys to trade securities, and rather than adapting the rules to those innovat=
ions, the SEC is demanding that those exchanges abandon the innovations and=
 conform to the traditional rules.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have said this before, but that=E2=80=99s th=
e sort of argument that people took seriously a year ago, and now do not. I=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMTMvdGhl=
LXNlYy1jcmFja3MtZG93bi1vbi1jcnlwdG8_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXR=
tX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDE3JnV0bV=
9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad131ace" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wro=
te in February</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I submit to you that the main fact=
 of crypto regulation in early 2023 is that regulators feel really burned b=
y the events of 2022, and particularly by the collapse of FTX. =E2=80=9CWe =
want to work with these nice smart young people who are building the financ=
ial system of the future, and I am sure that with their advice we can write=
=C2=A0smart regulations=C2=A0that protect=C2=A0consumers while still foster=
ing innovation=E2=80=9D was a totally normal thing for regulators (except t=
he SEC) to think and say in 2021. But now it is not! Now too many of those =
smart young people are under indictment or giving interviews from undisclos=
ed locations; too much customer money is gone.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nobody wants to hear it! Ooh, if we enforce tr=
aditional securities laws without adapting them to crypto, there will be no=
 crypto trading in the US: fine!=C2=A0The SEC=E2=80=99s majority view is ju=
st crystal clear here:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Virtually all crypto tokens are securi=
ties.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Securities cannot legally be=
 traded, in the US, except on a registered securities exchange.<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Hahaha good luck registering your=
 crypto exchange!</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Peirce says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During my time as a Commissioner, this agency =
repeatedly has urged firms seeking to sell crypto tokens or build crypto bu=
sinesses to come in and register. Many firms have responded to this call; t=
hey have engaged with staff and Commissioners intensively to determine whet=
her they need to register and, if so, how they might do so. With the except=
ion of a few token registrations and a very small number of ATSs employing =
a clunky (to satisfy regulatory demands) method of facilitating trades, no =
firm has been able to do so.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A Commission serious about regulating=E2=80=94=
and not destroying=E2=80=94this market would reflect on this near unblemish=
ed record of regulatory failure and do something about it. We would conside=
r the possibility that our rules, which in the past have evolved to address=
 the needs of, and the risks presented by, investors and firms in the tradi=
tional securities markets, might require some tweaking to permit firms to o=
ffer innovative ways of doing finance using novel technologies.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CA Commission serious about regulating=
=E2=80=94and not destroying=E2=80=94this market=E2=80=9D would <a href=3D"h=
