<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For most people, the biggest interest-rate bet=
 they will make in their lives is taking out a mortgage.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If you were a pretty sophisticated Wall Street professional =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0say, the president of Goldman Sachs Group Inc.? =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
and it was 2020, what sort of interest-rate bet would you want to make? Wel=
l, at least with the hindsight of 2023, =E2=80=9Cinterest rates in 2020 are=
 very low and they will probably go up from here=E2=80=9D would have been a=
 good bet, so you might have wanted to get short duration. So you=E2=80=99d=
 borrow as much money as you could=C2=A0at a low long-term fixed interest r=
ate. Most banks would give you a 30-year mortgage at a fixed rate, which is=
 a good start. But most mortgages amortize =E2=80=94=C2=A0you pay back some=
 of the principal each month =E2=80=94 which reduces their duration. If you=
=C2=A0wanted to be short a=C2=A0<em>lot=C2=A0</em>of duration, you might lo=
ok for a bank to give you a non-amortizing mortgage where you only pay inte=
rest, not principal, for many years. (Ideally you=E2=80=99d pay a very low =
interest rate because of your good credit and fancy job.) And then you coul=
d use the money to pay for a house that you could have bought with cash, an=
d invest the cash in very short-term investments =E2=80=94=C2=A0like bank d=
eposits? =E2=80=94=C2=A0so that it is available to deploy when rates go up.=
 You have borrowed long to lend short; you have effectively gotten yourself=
 an interest-rate swap where you pay a fixed rate and receive a floating ra=
te.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course most people do not take out mortgage=
s primarily to make interest-rate bets; most people take out mortgages beca=
use that=E2=80=99s how they can afford to buy a house. The president of Gol=
dman Sachs though ... probably more thoughtful about his interest-rate bets=
? Less likely to need the money, more likely to be doing a trade? More like=
ly to have a view on the path of rates, and a desire to get short duration?=
 More likely to shop around for the bank that will buy as much duration fro=
m him as possible?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Noah Buhayar, Jennife=
r Surane, Max Reyes and Ann Choi have a story about how First Republic Bank=
 sought out sophisticated rich customers, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTYvZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtcy1sb2Fucy10by1yaWNoLW=
NsaWVudHMtZHJhZy1lYXJuaW5ncy1oaW5kZXItcG90ZW50aWFsLXNhbGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxN=
zIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRt=
X3Rlcm09MjMwNDE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb=
495a371" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">  which was a mistake</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wealthy homebuyers and property investors with=
 high incomes and sterling credit scores could get a mortgage from First Re=
public Bank with a rock-bottom rate for several years. Better yet, they did=
n=E2=80=99t have to start repaying the principal for a decade.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Across Manhattan, the San Francisco Bay area a=
nd Southern California, those terms attracted legions of wealthy clients =
=E2=80=94 including executives from other banks =E2=80=94 as interest rates=
 sank during the pandemic. The loans left borrowers with more cash to inves=
t and spend than if they financed their properties with more conventional m=
ortgages. Demand was so strong that it helped First Republic double its ass=
ets in four years, while deposits surged. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The mortgages are performing well, but their l=
ow rates and delayed repayments hurt their value. =E2=80=A6 By the start of=
 this year, First Republic estimated its $137 billion stockpile of mortgage=
s would be worth about $19 billion less than their carrying value if sold o=
ff, its annual report shows. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">New York City property records from the past f=
ew years show customers came from all over the financial sector and include=
d industry leaders such as Goldman Sachs Group Inc. President John Waldron,=
 who took out an $11.2 million mortgage in June 2020, and R. Lawrence Roth,=
 a board member at Oppenheimer Holdings Inc. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0All of their lo=
ans had 10-year interest-only periods and rates starting below 3%.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes look if you are a regional bank and the pr=
esident of Goldman Sachs comes in and says =E2=80=9Chi I=E2=80=99d like to =
make an $11 million interest-rate bet with you,=E2=80=9D you are getting ad=
versely selected.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to think about the 2023 banking mini-c=
risis in the US is that the problem was with banks whose customers were too=
 sophisticated.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Silicon Valley Bank borrowed short to lend long and ended up with=
 a mark-to-market hole in its balance sheet when interest rates went up, bu=
t that=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
1193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjMtMDMtMTMvc3ZiLWNvdWxkbi10LWlnbm9yZS1pdHMtbG9zc2VzLWJ1dC10aGUtZmVkLWNhbj9=
jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDE3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bm=
V3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA0MTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB5e505755" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  a pretty common story</a> for any bank;=
 the problem at SVB was that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTQvc3ZiLXRvb2stdGhlLXdyb25nLXJpc2tzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTc=
yM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV=
90ZXJtPTIzMDQxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc=
142d2d1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">  all of its depositors</a> were venture-backed tech firms=
 who=C2=A0<em>noticed=C2=A0</em>that hole in the balance sheet, shared that=
 information with their networks, and acted quickly to protect themselves. =
They were too smart for <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTcvYmlnLWJhbmtzLXRydXN0LWZpcnN0LXJlcHVibGljLXdpdGgtdGhlaXIt=
bW9uZXk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4e7dc4fa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  their bank=E2=80=99s own good</=
a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly First Republic courted wealthy and s=
ophisticated clients with favorable mortgage rates. But wealthy and sophist=
icated clients are kind of a mixed bag! Sure they have the money to pay you=
 back; their=C2=A0<em>credit=C2=A0</em>is good. But the risk is that you=C2=
=A0will=C2=A0sell them products that are advantageous for them, and not so =
much for you.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Schwab</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A good price for a stock trade is $0. If you r=
un a retail brokerage and you charge customers $0 for stock trades, they wi=
ll tend to keep their money with you and=C2=A0do a lot of stock trades; if =
you charge them $4.99 they=E2=80=99ll say =E2=80=9Cmeh, stock trading, not =
great.=E2=80=9D Making stock trading frictionless is good for attracting st=
ock trading, and you are in the business of attracting stock trading.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it costs you money to do the trades =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0you need computers and customer service and so forth =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and so you need to pay for them somehow. And so a big question in modern=
 US retail stock brokerage is how brokers can make money to subsidize commi=
ssion-free stock trading. One=C2=A0approach that gets a lot of attention=C2=
=A0is payment for order flow: The broker can charge its customer $0 for a t=
rade, and then instead of paying to execute the trade on a stock exchange, =
it can get paid by a market maker that really wants to execute the trade. T=
his is hotly controversial for reasons we have <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2Etc=
HJlc3N1cmVzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxNzIzX01PTkVZU1RV=
RkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDE=
3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5ee81709" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">  discussed too many times</a>, and the US Securities and Exchange Commis=
sion has been <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3119=
3834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjI=
tMTItMTUvdGhlLXNlYy13YW50cy1tb3JlLXN0b2NrLWF1Y3Rpb25zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTcyM1=
9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90Z=
XJtPTIzMDQxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4384=
9bbd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">  working on rules to restrict it</a>, rules that might make =
it harder for brokers to offer commission-free trading.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is another, simpler, more popular=C2=
=A0approach, which is that most brokerage customers tend to have=C2=A0<em>c=
ash=C2=A0</em>in their brokerage accounts, cash that they have not yet inve=
sted in stocks. The brokerage can take that cash, invest it in safe bonds, =
earn some interest, pay a little of the interest to customers, keep the res=
t of it for itself, and subsidize free trading that way. That is, the broke=
rage can also be a bank, and make a net interest margin on the difference b=
etween what it pays customers on their deposits and what it earns from inve=
sting them.=C2=A0In 2019, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cua2FsenVtZXVzLmNvbS8yMDE5LzYvMjYvaG9=
3LWJyb2tlcmFnZXMtbWFrZS1tb25leS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb26cf85c" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> Patrick McKenzie pointed out</a> that =E2=80=9C57% of Schwab=E2=80=99s re=
venues are from net interest. The firm could literally give away every othe=
r service; discount the mutual fund fees to zero, do away with commissions,=
 etc etc, and they would still be profitable.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is possible that that was a low-rates pheno=
menon, or at least that it breaks down a bit when rates rise rapidly. Bloom=
berg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Annie Massa and Edward Harrison <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTQvc2Nod2FiLWVhcm5pbmdzLWJyb2tlcmFn=
ZS1mYWNlcy1mcmVzaC1yaXNrcy1pbi10aGUtemVyby1mZWUtbGFuZHNjYXBlLWl0LXNoYXBlZD9=
jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDE3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bm=
V3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA0MTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB7fa1502d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  reported last week</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Charles Schwab Corp. stunned Wall Street in 20=
19 by slashing trading commissions to zero, forcing its competitors to adap=
t. The move amounted to a big bet that its bank =E2=80=94 rather than its w=
ell-known discount brokerage =E2=80=94 would keep driving profits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a while, it worked to perfection. The pand=
emic hit, interest rates were pinned near historic lows, and Schwab raked i=
n billions as the fees it had forsaken were offset by what the company earn=
ed from its banking operation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But last month=E2=80=99s collapse of three US =
banks, the industry=E2=80=99s worst crisis since 2008, has turned that wage=
r on its head.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now Schwab, the biggest publicly traded US bro=
kerage, faces one of the most painful moments in its 50-year history. After=
 a rapid surge in interest rates, deposits sank while unrealized losses swe=
lled.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Schwab got customer cash and invested it in bo=
nds that lost money:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because Schwab generates most of its money fro=
m customer funds idling in low-yielding accounts =E2=80=94 which it =E2=80=
=9Csweeps=E2=80=9D into its bank arm =E2=80=94 the firm needed somewhere to=
 invest incoming cash as trading surged.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like Silicon Valley Bank, the largest of the t=
hree lenders that imploded last month, Schwab plowed into debt that will ta=
ke five years or more to mature. =E2=80=A6 The investments are now underwat=
er, though Schwab won=E2=80=99t have to book a loss unless it=E2=80=99s for=
ced to sell them.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And meanwhile the customer cash is drying up b=
ecause there are better rates elsewhere:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Whether the remaining deposits stay put will d=
epend to a degree on the big independent advisers that buttress Schwab=E2=
=80=99s business. They=E2=80=99re increasingly focused on getting the best =
returns for clients=E2=80=99 cash.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Charles Sachs, chief investment officer at Kau=
fman Rossin Wealth, is among them. He moves customer money from Schwab swee=
p accounts into its higher-yielding money-market funds, on almost a daily b=
asis.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When rates are very low and your brokerage cus=
tomers are YOLO=E2=80=99ing GameStop Corp. options, it is not really worth =
their time to move money from a cash sweep account earning 0% to a money-ma=
rket fund earning 0.5%. When rates go up, though, the money-market funds st=
art looking more attractive, and leaving cash idle to be ready to buy meme =
stocks is less attractive.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Schwab <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/31193834.260451/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTcvc2Nod2FiLWRlcG9zaXRzLWRyb3AtYXMtYnJva2VyY=
WdlLXBhdXNlcy1zaGFyZS1yZXB1cmNoYXNlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDE3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1=
dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA0MTcmdXR=
tX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb34555c4" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  r=
eported earnings today</a> and they were fine:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shares of Schwab rose 2.8% to $52.18 at 11:46 =
a.m. in New York, paring their decline this year to 37%. =E2=80=A6 Schwab=
=E2=80=99s customer deposits slid 11% since year-end to $325.7 billion as o=
f March 31. They=E2=80=99re down 30% from a year earlier, a drop that rough=
ly matched Wall Street estimates. =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a sign of strength, customers continued to =
add money to Schwab=E2=80=99s investment offerings. Core net new assets tot=
aled $132 billion, including more than $53 billion in March alone, the seco=
nd-most ever for that month.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s rapid interest r=
ate hikes buffeted Schwab=E2=80=99s business in recent quarters. Deposits, =
which underpin revenue, declined as customers moved away from lower-interes=
t accounts and looked for investments that provide better returns for their=
 excess cash. That trend is beginning to moderate, executives said Monday.<=
/p>
