 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> the complaint</a>, which =E2=80=9Casserts claims for br=
eaches of fiduciary duty=E2=80=9D against the directors. A sample:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Board=E2=80=99s decision to chase viewers =
by promoting the false stolen election claims has exposed the Company to pu=
blic ridicule and negatively impacted the credibility of Fox News as a medi=
a organization that is supposed to accurately report newsworthy events. The=
 Company is now the subject of two defamation cases, with combined damages =
claimed to exceed $4 billion. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Board=E2=80=99s failures caused and/or all=
owed the Company to sell a fictitious story of election fraud for the sole =
purpose of serving its own business purposes, in disregard for the truth, t=
he Board=E2=80=99s fiduciary obligations and the Company=E2=80=99s best int=
erests.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What a weird sentence. Surely =E2=80=9Cserving=
 [the Company=E2=80=99s] own business purposes=E2=80=9D is the main fiducia=
ry obligation of the board? More than credibility or avoiding ridicule? Lik=
e if the claim here was that Fox frittered away all of its money on things =
that the directors liked but that were bad for business, fine, but here the=
 claim is that the directors thought the election lies were distasteful but=
 <em>good</em> for business. I am not sure how that is a fiduciary breach.<=
/p>
